Vladimir Poutine and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a Third World War that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Poutine and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
At the end of this meeting, the two men released a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and sees his confirmation as a lifetime leader of China later in the year as a simple formality.
After concentrating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After securing Xi's support, Putin has set out to realize his life's dream with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar whom they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional even to sentimentality.
As a child, I met Russian soldiers many times when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise, being aware of his cruelty.
He reduced to rubble the capital of Chechnya, Grozny. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever operator of the KGB, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, it seems he has lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected that the Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers open-armed, but they turned out to be entirely on the same positions as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have put up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems unstoppable.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been tricked by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan' demonstrations in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The deep-rooted corruption in the awarding of defense contracts has also played an important role in his insufficient results.
Yet, instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He is sending the entire Russian army into battle and ignoring all the rules of war, including bombing civilians indiscriminately.
Many hospitals have been hit and the power grid that supplies the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia might well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already achieved wonders by managing to strengthen the determination and unity of the EU.
Pendant ce temps, Xi semble avoir réalisé que Poutine fait cavalier seul.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remain "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
